SIMPLE: envious
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Envious
<hw>En"vi*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>envios</ets>, F. <ets>envieux</ets>, fr. L. <ets>invidiosus</ets>,
fr. <ets>invidia</ets> envy. See <er>Envy</er>, and cf.
<er>Invidious</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Malignant; mischievous;
spiteful.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Each <qex>envious</qex> brier his weary legs doth scratch.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Feeling or exhibiting envy; actuated or directed by,
or proceeding from, envy; -- said of a person, disposition, feeling,
act, etc.; jealously pained by the excellence or good fortune of
another; maliciously grudging; -- followed by <xex>of</xex>,
<xex>at</xex>, and <xex>against</xex>; <as>as, an <ex>envious</ex> man,
disposition, attack; <ex>envious</ex> tongues.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My soul is <qex>envious</qex> of mine eye.</q>
<rj><qau>Keble.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Neither be thou <qex>envious</qex> at the wicked.</q>
<rj><qau>Prov. xxiv. 19.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Inspiring envy.</def> <mark>[Obs. or
Poetic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He to him leapt, and that same <qex>envious</qex> gage⟦br⟧
Of victor's glory from him snatched away.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Excessively careful; cautious.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No men are so <qex>envious</qex> of their health.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>En"vi*ous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>En"vi*ous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Environ</ent>⟦br⟧
